INSERT INTO public.email_teachings (theme, title, body_text, source_note) VALUES
('bhakti_devotion', 'The Stone That Was Never Punished', 'Ahalya''s story in the Ramayana is often mistold as a tale of punishment — the tradition''s deeper reading holds she was never condemned, only waiting in stillness for the right moment of release. Some seasons of stuckness, this story suggests, aren''t punishment either; they''re waiting for their own right moment.', 'Ahalyā — The Stone That Was Never Punished, Ramayana Codex'),
('bhakti_devotion', 'Choosing the Harder Path', 'Rama''s choice to accept exile rather than contest it is held up in this tradition not as passive resignation but as a conscious, deliberate choice — the harder path taken willingly rather than avoided. There''s a difference the Siddhas insist on between suffering that happens to you and difficulty you walk into with open eyes.', 'Rāma Chose the Exile — Ramayana Codex'),
('bhakti_devotion', 'The Misunderstood Catalyst', 'Kaikeyi, often cast as the villain of the Ramayana, is read in deeper Siddha commentary as playing a necessary catalytic role in the story''s unfolding — without her, the exile and everything it enabled would never have happened. The tradition asks you to consider who plays this role in your own life, and whether you''ve judged them too quickly.', 'Kaikeyī — The Most Misunderstood Being, Ramayana Codex'),
('bhakti_devotion', 'A Death That Was a Release', 'Dasharatha''s death in the epic is read not as tragedy alone but as the Atman — the soul — consciously releasing a body that had completed its purpose. Even endings, in this framing, can be understood as a kind of completion rather than only loss.', 'Daśaratha''s Death — The Ātman Releasing the Body, Ramayana Codex'),
('bhakti_devotion', 'Choosing to Be the Catalyst', 'Sita''s abduction, in certain Siddha readings of the Ramayana, is framed not as something that merely happened to her but as a role she is understood to have consciously accepted for the sake of what it would set in motion. It''s a radically different lens than the surface story suggests.', 'Sītā Chose to Be the Catalyst, Ramayana Codex'),
('bhakti_devotion', 'The Shining Distraction', 'The Golden Deer that lures Rama away from Sita is one of the Ramayana''s most quoted symbols of how something beautiful can still be a distraction from what actually matters. Worth asking, this week: what''s your golden deer right now?', 'The Golden Deer — The Shining Distraction, Ramayana Codex'),
('bhakti_devotion', 'The Inner Journey Encoded in Ordinary Life', 'Yogananda''s biography describes his father''s railway career as more than coincidence — in Siddha symbolic reading, the train becomes the inner energy channel, the stations become energy centers, the engine becomes life force itself. The tradition holds that ordinary circumstances often encode a deeper journey, if you know how to read them.', 'The Railway as Sushumna — Yogananda Codex'),
('bhakti_devotion', 'A Letter That Released Him', 'Twice in his youth, Yogananda used a single sealed letter — his mother''s foretelling of his path — to be released from arranged marriages that would have redirected his entire life. Sometimes the clearest boundary you can set is simply naming, clearly, what you already know to be true about your own path.', 'The Two Refused Marriages — Yogananda Codex'),
('longevity', 'Two Streams, One River', 'Ojas is described differently across the Charaka Samhita and the Thirumantiram — two related but distinct traditions converging on the same essential concept from different angles. Where two independent lineages agree, the Siddhas held, is usually where the deepest truth sits.', 'Ojas in Charaka Samhita vs Thirumantiram — Ojas Rasayana Academy'),
('longevity', 'Eight Drops in the Heart', 'Para Ojas, the subtlest form of vital essence, is described in classical texts as existing in a quantity as small as eight drops concentrated at the heart — vanishingly small, yet considered the difference between vitality and its absence. It''s a reminder that the most essential things in the body are rarely the largest.', 'Para Ojas vs Apara Ojas — Ojas Rasayana Academy'),
('longevity', 'The First Gate', 'Agastya Muni is said to have placed the cultivation of Ojas as the very first gate on the path toward Siddha longevity practice — before any advanced technique, this foundation had to be established first. Skipping foundations, in this tradition, was never considered a shortcut.', 'Why Agastya Muni placed Ojas-cultivation as the First Gate — Ojas Rasayana Academy'),
('ayurveda', 'The Fire That Burns Karma Burns Food First', 'Thirumoolar taught that the same inner fire capable of burning through accumulated karma also, more immediately, burns through food — meaning fasting practice was never separated from spiritual practice in this tradition, but understood as one continuous fire doing both jobs.', 'Thirumoolar on Tapas — Siddha Fasting Academy'),
('ayurveda', 'Fasting as Spiritual Technology', 'The 18 Siddhas'' collective teaching treats Upavasa not as a wellness technique borrowed by spirituality, but as spiritual technology in its own right — a tool built specifically to activate subtler states, with digestive rest as a side effect rather than the goal.', 'The 18 Siddhas'' Collective Teaching on Upavasa — Siddha Fasting Academy'),
('mediumship', 'Three Vehicles of Communication', 'Manas, Chitta, and Vak — mind, deeper consciousness, and speech — are mapped in Siddha mediumship teaching as three distinct vehicles, each carrying communication differently and requiring different training to use clearly. Most people only ever consciously develop one of the three.', 'The Three Vehicles of Communication — Siddha Mediumship Academy'),
('mediumship', 'Purification Before Power', 'Siddha teaching is explicit that psychic or mediumistic development attempted without purification first tends to create distortion rather than clarity — power without a clean channel amplifies noise, not signal. The tradition insists on sequence here for good reason.', 'Preparing the Vehicle — Purification Protocols, Siddha Mediumship Academy'),
('mediumship', 'What You Eat Changes What You Receive', 'The Pranic Diet Science teaches that food and frequency are directly linked to mediumship capacity — what you eat is held to shape not just physical energy but the clarity of subtle perception itself. Diet, in this tradition, was never treated as separate from spiritual sensitivity.', 'Food, Frequency & Mediumship Capacity — Siddha Mediumship Academy'),
('longevity', 'A Documented Rarity', 'Among Lahiri Mahasaya''s many disciples, the tradition names only three who are said to have achieved the most advanced Pancha-Vayu Samyama practice — a sober reminder that the deepest teachings in this lineage were never meant to be common, only available.', 'Pancha-Vayu Samyama — The Technical Basis, Yogananda Codex'),
('bhakti_devotion', 'Even Servants Reach Liberation', 'Jatayu, the vulture who dies attempting to rescue Sita, is granted what the tradition calls Moksha — liberation — for an act of devoted service, regardless of his form or status. The Ramayana is explicit here: liberation was never described as limited to the highly credentialed.', 'Jaṭāyu — Mokṣa of the Servant, Ramayana Codex');